   <text>
      <body>
         <head>To <persName>
                    <ptr target="../persons/pers0763">Samuel Furly</ptr>
                </persName>
            </head>
         <opener>
            <placeName>
               <region>London</region>
            </placeName>
            <lb/>
            <date when="1756-02-18">February 18, 1756</date>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <salute>Dear <persName>
                        <ptr target="../persons/pers0763">Sammy</ptr>
                    </persName>,</salute>
         </opener>
         <p>You are a very complaisant person. I know, in my little circle of acquaintance, more
            than twenty who have all <seg ana="ministerialQualifications ">the natural
               qualifications</seg> mentioned in the <index indexName="works">
                    <hi rend="italic">Address to the Clergy</hi>
                </index>,<note place="foot" n="1">
                    <persName>
                        <ptr target="../persons/pers0001">JW</ptr>
                    </persName>, <index indexName="works">
                        <hi rend="italic">An Address to the Clergy</hi> (1756); see <term cRef="33-34 14">
                            <hi rend="italic">Bibliography</hi>, No. 216, and vol. 14 of this
                     edn.</term>
                    </index>
                </note> and several others who have all the acquired ones,
            either by <seg ana="education">education</seg> or by <seg ana="grace">grace</seg>.<!--There's a parallel here to Wesley's moral psychology of habituated virtue: natural, acquired, infused, etc.-->
            And I would engage to take <age value="14">any person of fourteen years of age</age>,
               <pb n="12"/>who has good natural abilities, and <seg ana="education">to teach him in
               seven years <seg ana="ministerialQualifications">everything which is there
                  required</seg>, to a good degree of perfection</seg>.</p>
         <p>
                <foreign lang="Latin">
                    <hi rend="italic">Ex pede <seg ana="GreekMythology">Herculem</seg>
                    </hi>
                </foreign>.<note place="foot" n="2">A Latin proverb:
                  <gloss>'[You can tell it is] <seg ana="GreekMythology">
                            <persName>Hercules</persName>
                        </seg> from his foot'.</gloss>
                </note> You
            may easily see what <seg ana="Latin">Latin</seg> I write by one of the <bibl>
                    <foreign lang="Latin">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dissertationes in <index Jobum="Job" indexName="biblical">
                                <term cRef="Job">Jobum</term>
                            </index>
                        </hi>
                    </foreign>
                </bibl>;<note place="foot" n="3">
                    <persName>
                        <ptr target="../persons/pers2190">Samuel Wesley
                  <genName>Sr.</genName>
                        </ptr>
                    </persName>'s <foreign lang="Latin">
                        <hi rend="italic">magnum opus</hi>
                    </foreign> on <index indexName="biblical">
                        <term cRef="Job">Job</term>
                    </index>, to which <persName>
                        <ptr target="../persons/pers0001">JW</ptr>
                    </persName> contributed much both in
               research and by <seg ana="Latin">translations into Latin</seg>; <index indexName="works">
                        <term cRef="33-34">see <hi rend="italic">Bibliography</hi>, No.
                     7.</term>
                    </index>
                </note> or even by <index indexName="works">the short
               conversation with <persName>
                        <ptr target="../persons/pers2310">Count
                  Zinzendorf</ptr>
                    </persName> which is printed in the <hi rend="italic">Journal</hi>.<note place="foot" n="4">
                        <persName>
                            <ptr target="../persons/pers0001">JW</ptr>
                        </persName>, <hi rend="italic">Journal</hi>, <date when="1741-09-03">Sept. 3, 1741</date>, <term cRef="19:211-215">19:211–15 in
                     this edn.</term>
                    </note>
                </index> I do not know that I have any theme or
            declamation left.<note place="foot" n="5">I.e., <seg ana="Latin">exercises in
                  Latin</seg> that <persName>
                        <ptr target="../persons/pers0001">JW&gt;</ptr>
                    </persName>
               would have prepared while a student at
                  <placeName>
                        <institution>Oxford</institution>
                    </placeName>.</note> But why do you
            not talk <seg ana="Latin">Latin</seg> when you are with me? Do this, and you will see
            the excellence of <persName>Terence</persName>'s language; whereas <persName>
                    <ptr target="http://viaf.org/viaf/61387892">Tully</ptr>
                </persName> [i.e.,
                  <persName>
                    <ptr target="http://viaf.org/viaf/61387892">Cicero</ptr>
                </persName>]
            would make you talk like a mere stiff pedant.</p>
         <p>
                <bibl>
                    <persName>
                        <ptr target="http://viaf.org/viaf/61387892">Randal</ptr>
                    </persName>'s Geographical Grammar</bibl>
                <note place="foot" n="6">
                    <persName>
                        <ptr target="../persons/pers0001">Wesley</ptr>
                    </persName> is likely
               referring to <bibl>
                        <persName>
                            <ptr target="http://viaf.org/viaf/61387892">Joseph
                        Randall</ptr>
                        </persName>'s <hi rend="italic">A System of Geography</hi>
                  (1744)</bibl>, which he placed on the reading list for
                     <placeName>
                        <institution>Kingswood School</institution>
                    </placeName> (the fifth
               class) in <date when="1748">1748</date>; <index term="Minutes" indexName="works"><!--Another ugly tag, but it works!-->see Minutes, <date when="1748-06-04">June
                     4, 1748</date>, Q. 11, <term cRef="10:217">10:217 in this
               edn.</term>
                    </index>
                </note> is the best compendium of <seg ana="geography">geography</seg> which I have seen; and you need nothing more on <seg ana="geography">that subject</seg>, adding only the <hi rend="italic">terrestrial globe</hi>.</p>
         <p>If you are master of <seg ana="metaphysics ontology pneumatology">
                    <bibl>
                        <persName>
                            <ptr target="http://viaf.org/viaf/51735420">Hutcheson</ptr>
                        </persName>'s
                  Metaphysics</bibl>
                    <note place="foot" n="7">
                        <bibl>[<persName>
                                <ptr target="http://viaf.org/viaf/51735420">Francis
                     Hutcheson</ptr>
                            </persName>,] <hi rend="italic">
                                <foreign lang="Latin">Synopsis
                           Metaphysicae Ontologiam et Pneumatologiam complectans</foreign>
                            </hi>
                     (1742)</bibl>; see also <index indexName="works">
                            <term cRef="27:25-26">
                                <persName>
                                    <ptr target="../persons/pers0001">JW</ptr>
                                </persName>'s letter to <persName>
                                    <ptr target="../persons/pers0763">Furly</ptr>
                                </persName> of <date when="1756-03-14">Mar. 14, 1756</date>
                            </term>
                        </index>.</note>
                </seg> and
                  <bibl>
                    <seg ana="ontology">
                        <persName>
                            <ptr target="http://viaf.org/viaf/49234977">Clerc</ptr>
                        </persName>'s <foreign lang="Latin">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ontologia</hi>
                        </foreign>
                    </seg>
                </bibl>,<note place="foot" n="8">One of the
               early works of the prolific <nationality>Dutch</nationality> scholar, <persName>
                        <ptr target="http://viaf.org/viaf/49234977">Jean Le Clerc</ptr>
                    </persName> (<date from="1657-03-19" to="1736-01-08">1657–1736</date>). It formed the second of three
               parts of <seg ana="logic ontology pneumatology">a Latin work on logic, ontology, and
                  pneumatology</seg>, first published in <date when="1692">1692</date> and dedicated
               to <persName>
                        <ptr target="http://viaf.org/viaf/34459614">John
               Locke</ptr>
                    </persName>.</note> I advise you to look no farther that way; unless you
            would add <bibl>
                    <persName>
                        <ptr target="http://viaf.org/viaf/66545180">Malebranche</ptr>
                    </persName>'s <hi rend="italic">Search after
               Truth</hi>
                </bibl>,<note place="foot" n="9">
                    <persName>
                        <ptr target="../persons/pers0001">Wesley</ptr>
                    </persName> read <bibl>
                        <persName>
                            <ptr target="http://viaf.org/viaf/66545180">Nicholas
                  Malebranche</ptr>
                        </persName>'s <foreign lang="French">
                            <hi rend="italic">De la
                        Recherche de la Verité</hi>
                        </foreign> (<date when="1674">1674</date>)</bibl>
               in French in <date when="1733">1733</date>; he frequently recommended the translated
               form, <bibl>
                        <hi rend="italic">Father <persName>
                                <ptr target="http://viaf.org/viaf/66545180">Malebranche</ptr>
                            </persName>'s Treatise concerning the Search After
                     Truth</hi>, translated by <persName>Thomas Taylor</persName> (<date when="1694">1694</date>)</bibl>.</note> or <persName>
                    <ptr target="../persons/pers0292">the
                  Bishop of Cork</ptr>
                </persName>'s two books<note place="foot" n="10">For
                     <persName>
                        <ptr target="../persons/pers0292">Peter Browne, <occupation>Bishop of
                              <placeName>
                                    <region>Cork</region>
                                </placeName>
                            </occupation>
                        </ptr>
                    </persName>,
                  <term cRef="25:251">see 25:251 in this edn.</term>, where <persName>
                        <ptr target="../persons/pers0001">Wesley</ptr>
                    </persName> recommended
                        <bibl>
                        <persName>
                            <ptr target="../persons/pers0292">Browne</ptr>
                        </persName>'s <hi rend="italic">Procedure, Extent, and Limits of
                     Human Understanding</hi> (<date when="1728">1728</date>)</bibl> to
                     <persName>
                        <ptr target="../persons/pers0844">Mary Pendarves</ptr>
                    </persName>.
               The second book would be <bibl>
                        <persName>
                            <ptr target="../persons/pers0292">Browne</ptr>
                        </persName>'s <hi rend="italic">Things Supernatural and
                     Divine conceived by Analogy with Things Natural and Human</hi> (<date when="1733">1733</date>)</bibl>; <index indexName="works">see <persName>
                            <ptr target="../persons/pers0001">JW</ptr>
                        </persName>, <hi rend="italic">A Letter
                     to <persName>
                                <ptr target="../persons/pers1261">the Reverend Mr.
                        Law</ptr>
                            </persName>
                        </hi> (<date when="1756-01-06">1756</date>), §II.7,
                     <term cRef="14">vol. 14 in this edn.</term>
                    </index>
                </note> again.</p>
         <p>The main point is, with all and above all, study <seg ana="scripture">the <seg ana="GreekNewTestament">Greek</seg> and <seg ana="HebrewBible">Hebrew
               Bible</seg>
                </seg>, and <seg ana="GodsLove">the love of</seg>
            <seg ana="Christ">Christ</seg>.</p>
         <closer>I am, <signed>Yours affectionately,<lb/>
               <persName>
                        <ptr target="../persons/pers0001">J. Wesley</ptr>
                    </persName>
            </signed>
         </closer>
      </body>
      <p>
            <hi rend="italic">Address</hi>: 'To / <persName>
                <ptr target="../persons/pers0763">Mr
               Sam. Furley</ptr>
            </persName> / In <placeName QueensCollegeCambridg.="QueensCollege,Cambridge">
                <institution>Queen's College /
               Cambridg.</institution>
            </placeName>'.</p>
